@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@next "Requirements"
@prev "Main"
Some text editors (e.g. GoldEd and ProgED) can expand words, i.e. look up a
word in a list and replace it with one or more words. My preferred editor,
PolyEd, can't do this, so one afternoon I booted my Amiga with the intention
of writing a simple macro for expanding. I got the idea that I should write
the word searching part in C, to speed up things. A few hours later I had a
simple version which waited for a word to to be sent to the ARexx port, and
when that happened, returned a replacement string. Then it started to
grow...

The result is @{fg highlight}RExpand@{fg text}.

RExpand is an ARexx host which will expand words. So if your text editor
have an ARexx interface, it can communicate with RExpand via an Arexx
script. Not only text editors can use RExpand, any program with an ARexx
port can use it. So you can use RExpand with a data base program to simplify
input of data, or you could let it enter complex formulas in a spreadsheat
with just a few keypresses. Even word processors like FinalWriter or
WordWorth 5 can use RExpand!

Features:
  - A @{"requester" link "Requester" 0} can be opened if there is several possible matches, to let
    the user choose the correct replacement string. The requester can be
    opened on any public screen.

  - @{"ARexx scripts" link "Editors" 0} are included for the editors PolyEd, Annotate, Edt,
    BlacksEditor, TKEd and SkoEd.

  - Small! Uses only 30 kb of memory when running.

  - Several @{"shell utilites" link "Utilities" 0} are included.

  - Replacement strings can be written to a @{"file" link "ArexxCommand" 77}.

  - @{"Data files" link "DataFiles" 0} can be located anywhere, and can be added and removed
    with an @{"ARexx command" link "ArexxCommand" 43}.

  - Data files for the Amiga @{"includes" link "Includes" 0} are supplied, with ARexx macros for
    generating these files as well.

  - Data files can be edited with an ordinary text editor; no need for a
    preferences program.

  - If there is more than one match, all found replacement strings can be
    returned in a @{"stem variable" link "ArexxCommand" 30}.

  - Replacement strings can contain @{"escaped characters" link "EscapeChar" 0} for newlines, tabs
    or any other special character.

  - @{"Source code" link "Source" 0} is included, with public domain status.
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
@next "Legal"
@prev "Introduction"
Requirements:
 - OS 2.04 or newer
 - ARexx must be running
 - 30 kb free memory =)

Tested on:
 * A1200, 68EC020/14 Mhz, Chip 2 Mb, Fast 0 Mb
 * A1200, 68EC030/28 Mhz + FPU 68881/33 Mhz, Chip 2 Mb, Fast 8 Mb

RExpand was...
  ...developed on my humble A1200 (vanilla except for an 85 Mb harddisk,
     but soon I'll get a Cobra 030/28/4 accellerator :)
  ...written in C (@{"source" link "Source" 0} is included)
  ...typed in PolyEd by Robert Brander
  ...compiled with DICE by Matt Dillon
  ...infinitely helped by KingCon by David Larsson (Get it! Now! The
     filename completion (and a lot of other useful features) will save
     your poor fingers even more than RExpand ;)
@endnode

