@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Start"
@prev "Legal"
There's a few files and drawers in this package:

  RExpand           -- RExpand itself
  RExpand.guide     -- This guide
  Install_RExpand   -- An installation script
  Source (dir)      -- @{"Source code" link "Source" 0}
  Editors (dir)     -- @{"ARexx scripts for some editors" link "Editors" 0}
  Data (dir)        -- @{"Data files" link "DataFiles" 0} for the @{"includes" link "Includes" 0}
  Utils (dir)       -- A few useful @{"shell utilities" link "Utilities" 0}

@{b}SIMPLE:@{ub}
 A script is included for the standard C= installer. Just click it.

@{b}DIY:@{ub}
 Copy the stuff you want wherever you want it. No assigns are needed. If you
want RExpand to start when you boot you either have to copy it into
WBStartup or modify User-Startup.

@{i}Note: @{ui}The installation script will detect if ARexx is running. If it isn't
running the needed instruction will be added to User-Startup so ARexx is
started every time you boot. (The program findrexx (by me, 80 bytes :) does
that. Returns 0 if ARexx is running, 5 otherwise.)
@endnode

@node "Start" "Starting RExpand"
@next "Search"
@prev "Installation"
RExpand can be started both from the Shell and the Workbench, and its setup
can be controlled by arguments or tooltypes. RExpand can't be made resident,
but you can have several copies running at any time (as long as they have
different port names).

                                   *****

 Argument: PORTNAME/K
 Tooltype: PORTNAME

This will be the name of RExpand's ARexx port. If this port already exists,
RExpand will return WARN and print a warning message. The default port name
is "REXPAND". NB: The port name is case sensitive.

                                   *****

 Argument: FILES/M
 Tooltype: FILE      (You can have several FILE tooltypes to add more than
                     one file.)

Adds data files to the @{"file list" link "FileList" 0}. If not specified no files will be added.

                                   *****

 Argument: DATADIR/K
 Tooltype: DATADIR

Change the path of the default @{"data files" link "DataFiles" 0}. The default path is
"PROGDIR:Data/". If the specified directory doesn't exist or can't be
locked, the default will be used.

                                   *****

 Argument: NODEF=NODEFFILES/S
 Tooltype: NODEFFILES    (No value)

RExpand will never search in any default data file, only in the files in the
file list and those given with the @{"ARexx command" link "ArexxCommand" 0}. (Using DATADIR with
NODEFFILES is quite pointless...)
@endnode

@node "Search" "How the search works"
@next "DataFiles"
@prev "Start"
When RExpand recieves an @{"ARexx command" link "ArexxCommand" 0} it will search one or more @{"data files" link "DataFiles" 0}
for the word which should be expanded. Depending on the arguments in the
command, it will either stop when it finds a matching word, or proceed with
the search to find all the matches.

A word in a data file matches the the search word when it begins with the
search word (this is case insensitive). An example: a search for "alloc"
would match "Alloc", "AllocMem" and "aLLoccurances", but not "all".

The search order of the files is:
 * Files passed with the "FILES" argument, when neither "ADD" or "REMOVED"
   are used. If "ONLY" is used, stop the search after these files (even if
   no match is found.)
 * Files in the @{"file list" link "FileList" 0}, in the order they were added.
 * Default data files (unless "NODEFFILES" was used at @{"startup" link "Start" 0}) in the 
   order:
     * "?.data", where '?' is the first character of the search word. If
       this isn't an alphabetic character, skip to the next item.
     * ".data"

The use of "REQUESTER", "STEM" or "ALL" will search all of these files to
find all the matches. Otherwise the search will stop as soon as a match is
found.

When RExpand finds a matching word, the @{"replacement string" link "DataFiles" 0} will be returned,
written to a file, added to a list etc. If there isn't a replacement string
the found word will be returned. This, combined with the search method
explained above, gives the ability to expand single words or to give them
the correct capitalization without the need for a replacement string.
@endnode

@node "DataFiles" "Data files"
@next "EscapeChar"
@prev "Search"
RExpand must know what it should replace a word with. To do this, it
@{"searches" link "Search" 0} through a number of data files for the word. These files can be
located anywhere, but there are a few special data files.

These default data files have the filename style "?.data", where '?' is an
alphabetic character (A-Z). All the words in a default data file begins with
the character '?'. Words which doesn't begin with an alphabetic character
will be searched for in the file ".data". Alph.chars words can be placed
here as well; the search can proceed in this file after the "?.data" file.

The default data files are placed in a special directory. By default, this
is assumed to be "PROGDIR:Data/" (the directory "Data" in the directory
where RExpand is), but you can change it at @{"startup" link "Start" 0}. You can also @{"disable" link "Start" 0}
the searching of these files.

                                   *****

The data files contains a number of entries which defines how a word should
be expanded. One line may contain one entry, and an entry can't be spread
over several lines. Only the first 511 characters of a line will be used.
Empty lines will be ignored.

The entry syntax:
 word [["]replacement string["]]

'word' is the word which should expand to 'replacement string'. If that
string is ommited 'word' will expand to itself. (see @{"search" link "Search" 0} for more info).
'word' mustn't contain spaces or tabs, but can be surrounded by any number
of blanks.

'replacement string' can be either quoted or not quoted:
 * When it isn't quoted it will start with the first non-blank character
   following 'word', and end with the last non-blank character on the line.
 * When it is quoted it will begin with the character following the quote,
   and end with the character before the last quote. If the last quote is
   omitted, the string will end on the last character of the line, even if
   it's blank. 'replacement string' can contain @{"escaped characters" link "EscapeChar" 0}.
@endnode

@node "EscapeChar" "Escaped characters"
@next "FileList"
@prev "DataFiles"
The @{"replacement string" link "DataFiles" 0} can use escaped characters to allow unprintable
characters (such as newline, tab etc.) in the strings.

An escaped characters begins with a '\' (a backslash), followed by one
character:

 '\n': a newline
 '\t': a tab
 '\\': the '\' character itself.
 '\"': a quote '"'. Only necessary to use when the string is quoted.

You can represent any other character with it's ascii code. This is done by
follow the backslash with a decimal value (ex: '\64' will give '@'). You can
also use a hexadecimal value by putting an 'x' or an 'X' before the value
(ex: '\x5b' will give ']'). When a character which isn't a digit (or A-F in
hex) is read the escape sequence will be replaced by the character with an
ascii code of the value read so far. RExpand won't read any more digits if
the value would be greater than 255. It will never read more than 3 digits
with decimal values, and 2 digits with hexadecimal values.

Example: The string 'I\x74em \350' will become 'Item #0'
@endnode

@node "FileList" "Data file list"
@next "ArexxCommand"
@prev "EscapeChar"
RExpand can keep a list of @{"data files" link "DataFiles" 0} to be included in the @{"search" link "Search" 0}. These
files can be added at startup, or later added or removed from ARexx. They
will be searched before all default files.

By using this feature you can have a set of standard files (e.g. the data
files for the @{"includes" link "Includes" 0}) which you don't modify, and put all you own strings
in a separate data file. Then add this file to the file list and you don't
have to mess around with the (quite big) default data files.
@endnode

@node "ArexxCommand" "The ARexx command"
@next "Requester"
@prev "FileList"
RExpand has only one ARexx command, but it's a huge beast:

 EXPAND/K,VAR/K,STEM/K,FILES/K/M,ADD/S,REMOVE/S,ONLY/S,DATADIR/K,
 REQUESTER/S,REQTITLE/K,REQSCREEN/K,TO/K,ALL/S,QUIT/S

The expand string will be return in RESULT if you have specified OPTIONS
RESULTS in the ARexx script. RC will be set to one of these return values:

  0: All went well, and a matching expand string was found. Will also be
     returned if no search was performed, because EXPAND wasn't given.
  5: No expand string was found, or the user cancelled the @{"requester" link "Requester" 0} if it
     is used.
 10: An error in the command line.

If there isn't enough memory, or a file can't be found, RExpand won't notify
you on this.

The expand string will be the first matching string found, or the string the
user choose in the @{"requester" link "Requester" 0} if it is used.

                                   *****

@{fg highlight}EXPAND/K:@{fg text}
 This is the word to be expanded. The keyword is required so the word
doesn't mess up the command if it should be the same as another keyword.
Without EXPAND, no @{"search" link "Search" 0} will be done.

                                   *****

@{fg highlight}VAR/K:@{fg text}
 If you use this RExpand will set the ARexx variable <VAR> to the expand
string.

@{fg highlight}STEM/K:@{fg text}
 RExpand will search all the data files and put all the found strings in the
stem variable <STEM>. If STEM is 'EXPAND.', EXPAND.0 will hold the number of
strings found, and the strings will be put in EXPAND.i, where i is a number
from 1 to EXPAND.0
 NB: <STEM> must end in a dot.

                                   *****

@{fg highlight}FILES/K/M, ADD/S, REMOVE/S, ONLY/S:@{fg text}
 If only FILES is given this is one or more files to be included in the
@{"search" link "Search" 0}. If ADD is set the files will be added to the end of the @{"file list" link "FileList" 0},
which means that they will be searched later. If REMOVE is set the files
will be removed from the file list, and they won't be searched. If ONLY is
set, only these files will be searched. The files in the file list and the
@{"default files" link "DataFiles" 0} will be ignored then.

 RExpand will try to find the files relative to the current dir first, and
if that fails it will search for them in the @{"data dir" link "DataFiles" 0}. If the file can't be
found, it will be ignored. RExpand always work with a lock on the actual
files, never with the file name. As long as you reference the same file,
RExpand doesn't care about what path you use, or the capitalization of the
file name (handy for REMOVE.)

                                   *****

@{fg highlight}DATADIR/K:@{fg text}
 Changes the directory of the @{"default files" link "DataFiles" 0} for this search only.

                                   *****

@{fg highlight}REQUESTER/S, REQTITLE/K, REQSCREEN/K:@{fg text}
 If there is more than one match, REQUESTER brings up a @{"requester" link "Requester" 0} (who'd've
guessed that 8-) to let the user choose the string he/she want. You can
specify your own requester title with REQTITLE (the default is @{i}"RExpand
theword (nr matches)"@{ui}). You can use '%d' in the title to show the number of
matches. Remember to qoute the title string if it contains spaces. The
requester is usually opened on the default public screen, but with REQSCREEN
you can specify the name of a public screen to open the requester on. If the
screen doesn't exist the default public screen will be used.

                                   *****

@{fg highlight}TO/K, ALL/S:@{fg text}
 TO puts the expand string in the file <TO> (if the file already exists it
will be replaced.) If you set ALL, all the matches will be output to the
file. If the @{"requester" link "Requester" 0} is used at the same time as ALL, the choosen expand
string will be printed first in the file, then a empty line, then all the
found matches.

                                   *****

@{fg highlight}QUIT/S:@{fg text}
 This will cause RExpand to quit (after any @{"search" link "Search" 0}).
@endnode

@node "Requester" "The requester"
@next "Editors"
@prev "ArexxCommand"
RExpand can open a requester to let the user choose between all the @{"matching" link "Search" 0}
@{"replacement strings" link "Search" 0}. This requester is fontsensitive, adopt itself to the
window size and can be controlled from the keyboard.

The requester contains a listview gadget with all the found strings, sorted
alphabetically.

To choose a string, double click on it; or close the window if you don't
want any of the strings found.

You can also control the requester with the cursor keys, choose a string
with return, or cancel the requester with esc. Pressing shift while moving
with the cursor keys, will move the select bar several items up or down, and
pressing alt will go to the top or the bottom of the list.
@endnode

@node "Editors" "Editor Macros"
@next "Utilities"
@prev "Editors"
The best use of RExpand is with an text editor. Then you need an ARexx
script (macro) that handles the communication between the editor and
RExpand.

In the drawer "Editors" there are scripts for some editors included.
(Consult the docs for your editor to see how to run the script from the
editor.)

 * Annotate/Expand.rexx
    @{fg highlight}For Annotate by Doug Bakewell@{fg text}
    The cursor must be positioned on the word you want to expand.

 * BlacksEditor/Expand.bed
    @{fg highlight}For BlacksEditor by Marco Negri@{fg text}

 * Edt/Expand.edt
    @{fg highlight}For Edt by Joachim Barheine@{fg text}

 * PolyEd/Expand.ped
    @{fg highlight}For PolyEd by Robert Brandner@{fg text}
    The cursor mustn't be positioned on the first character of the word.
    This is caused by a bug in PolyEd. Any distance to the right of the
    word is alright, though.

 * SkoEd/Expand.rexx
    @{fg highlight}For SkoEd by David McPaul@{fg text}
    This macro have some serios problems, since the function for getting
    the word the cursor is over loses the first character X-(
    Feel free to try to fix it.

 * TKEd/Expand.tked
    @{fg highlight}For TKed by Tom Kroener@{fg text}
    TKEd's screen isn't public so RExpand can't open the @{"requester" link "Requester" 0} there.
    The requester will appear on the default public screen instead :(


Except for PolyEd, which has the honour of being my preferred editor, all
these editors was downloaded from Aminet just so I could write script for
them. I had some serious problems with Edt and another editor called Eddy
though: the documentation was only in German, which I can't speak to save my
A1200 ;) I managed to extract some information for Edt, but I failed with
Eddy. Please guys, write docs in English as well!

When I get hold of more editors I will write macros for them as well. If you
need a script for another editor try to write it yourself.

It's quite simple: find out which word the cursor is over, send it to
RExpand who respondes with a replacement string, delete the word and insert
the replacement string.

Consult your editor's docs to find out how to do this exactly. You can also
get some additional help from the included scripts.

If you have written a script, please send it to me so I can include it in a
future release. You can also upload it on Aminet, if you want.
@endnode

@node "Utilities" "The shell utilities"
@next "Includes"
@prev "Editors"
There's a few shell utilites in the drawer Utils:

                                   *****

rx QuitRExpand [portname]

QuitRExpand is an ARexx script which will send a 'QUIT' command to the
RExpand port 'portname', or to 'REXPAND' if portname isn't given.

                                   *****

Expand WORD,PORTNAME/K,QUIET/S,FILES/M/K,ADD/S,REMOVE/S,ONLY/S,
    DATADIR/K,REQUESTER/S,REQSCREEN/K,REQTITLE/K,TO/K,ALL/S

Expand is a shell script which makes it possible to use RExpand from shell.
Except for WORD, PORTNAME and QUIET all the arguments are the same as the
@{"ARexx command" link "ArexxCommand" 0}. WORD is the word to expand, PORTNAME is the RExpand port to
use ('REXPAND' if not given). By default Expand will print the replacement
string on the console, but if you use QUIET it won't do this. Expand uses
the ARexx macro Rexx_Expand.rexx, which @{i}must @{ui}be located in REXX:. Do not try
to use Rexx_Expand.rexx directly; you can't wreck your computer, but it is
much easier to use Expand.

                                   *****

Includes2DataFile and Proto2DataFile are discussed @{"here" link "Includes" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Includes" "NDK Includes data files"
@next "Source"
@prev "Utilities"
There are two ARexx scripts called Includes2DataFile and Proto2DataFile. You
can use these to create @{"data files" link "DataFiles" 0} with all the defines, structs, struct
members and prototypes in the Amiga includes. Precreated data files are
included in the package in the drawer Data/.

The data files are used in this way:
 * Type the first character for defines, struct members and prototypes. The
   full name with the correct capitalization will substitute the word
   you've started.
 * Type the first characters of the struct's name and it will be expanded 
   to "struct FullName", where "FullName" is the struct's name, correctly 
   capitalized. You must have an @{"ARexx script for your editor" link "Editors" 0}, though.

Includes2DataFile and Proto2DataFile are written in ARexx. This means that
they are slow, but easy to modify if you want data files for e.g.
assembler.

You use the scripts in this way:

 rx Includes2DataFile <IncludesDir> <DataDir>
 rx Proto2DataFile <IncludesDir> <DataDir>

IncludesDir is where all the Amiga includes are installed on your system
(e.g. INCLUDE:), and DataDir is where you want the @{"data files" link "DataFiles" 0}. If there's
already some data files in this dir, the new data will be appended to these
files. The difference between Includes... and Proto... is that the former
doesn't process the prototypes headers in clib/ or in proto/, but the latter
only does that. Run them in any order you want.
@endnode

@node "Source" "The C source code"
@next "Author"
@prev "Includes"
The source code for RExpand is included in the drawer Source/. They are
written in C with DICE, but it should be easy to compile the source with
another compiler. The code is commented, and there's some examples of ARexx
port programming, writing resizable GUI's and reading command arguments and
tooltypes.

Here is the source code licence, as included in the source files:

/**************************************************************************

Source code for RExpand (which is Copyright ©1996 Peter Liljenberg)

Version 1.0 Author: Peter Liljenberg, 1996.

This code is fully Public Domain: you can use it in any way you want as long
as you don't violate the copyright of the _program_ RExpand. This means that
you can use the code for inspiration, for help or as an example; and you can
even cut code out and include it in your own programs, as long as you don't
make a program which, basicly, is RExpand and release it. You can make
modifications or add features to RExpand for your own use (and maybe some
friends' as well), but I'd be grateful if you would send me the modified
code so I can make a new version with this stuff added. You will get due
credit for the changes. In the same way, I expect to get a mention in the
docs if you make a program with any help of this code.

If this code in any way cause damage or loss of data, I'm not responsible;
you are.

**************************************************************************/
@endnode

@node "Author" "Who is Peter Liljenberg?"
@next "Main"
@prev "Source"
My address:
    Peter Liljenberg
    Repslagaregatan 40
    S-582 22 Linköping
    Sweden (Europe)

E-mail:
    c96petli@und.ida.liu.se

The email address will be valid into the next millenium, but my postal
address may change (it will be valid for a year or so, though).

                                   *****

 You: Peter, is RExpand your first released program?
 I:   No, there's a program called IconConvert. It converts the image of an
      icon from one palette to another, in such a way that the image isn't
      lost. I wrote it when I wanted to use MagicWB icons on a four colour
      screen.
 You: Why?
 I:   To save memory, harddisk space and time. People which haven't got a
      souped-up Amiga need every little byte they can get hold of. At least
      I do. Just setting the screen to use four colours results in
      horrendous images. IconConvert solves this problem.
 You: Fascinating. Where can I find it?
 I:   Aminet of course, util/wb/iconconv.lha. That's v1.2. AmigaShopper had
      v1.1 on their coverdisks in issue #59. I'm currently working on v2.0,
      which will feature so many new features that I've change the name.
 You: Can you mention some of the improvements?
 I:   Why, certainly. An intelligent scaling which will try to keep the
      details of the image, adding and removing of tooltypes, you'll be
      able to change the default tool to your favourite programs. All of
      this can be done one or more times, you can also specify what the
      requirements are for processing an icon (e.g. the icon's name, the
      default tool, image depth). This means that you can set IconVert to
      recognise e.g. AmigaGuide files and then set the default tool to
      AmigaGuide, or to MuchMore (or your preferred viewer) if it is an
      text file, or to remove NewIcon tooltypes if there are any; the sky's
      the limit!
      All of the processing will then be done automagically when you drop
      an icon on IconVert's appicon.
 You: Cool! But, you just said IconVert; wasn't the name IconConvert?
 I:   As I said, I've changed the name. It will be finished in, say, 
      October or November 1996.
 You: I'll keep an eye on Aminet!
 I:   Then look for "util/wb/IconVert.lha".
 You: I will!

                                   *****

